03779nam a22005535i 9780520389601DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20222022cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2022018546  a97805203896017 a10.1525/97805203896012doi  a(DE-B1597)627308  a(OCoLC)1347247157  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aF868.S25 4aF868.S25bT63 2023 7aHIS0520002bisacsh04a979.4/73223/eng/202205181 aTodd, Anne Marie, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aValley of Heart's Delight :bEnvironment and Sense of Place in the Santa Clara Valley /cAnne Marie Todd. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (207 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tOne. The World’s Largest Orchard: Valley as Natural Wonder -- tTwo. Prune Pickers and ’Cot Cutters: Valley as Fruit Factory -- tThree. From Farmland to Metropolis: Valley as Symbol of Progress -- tFour. Conclusion -- tResearch Notes -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis agricultural history explores the transformation of the Santa Clara Valley over the past one hundred years from America's largest fruit-producing region into the technology capital of the world. In the latter half of the twentieth century, the region's focus shifted from fruits—such as apricots and prunes—to computers. Both personal and public rhetoric reveals how a sense of place emerges and changes in an evolving agricultural community like the Santa Clara Valley. Through extensive archival research and interviews, Anne Marie Todd explores the concepts of place and placelessness, arguing that place is more than a physical location and that exploring a community's sense of place can help us to map how individuals experience their natural surroundings and their sense of responsibility towards the local environment. Todd extends the concept of sense of place to describe Silicon Valley as a non-place, where weakened or disrupted attachment to place threatens the environment and community. The story of the Santa Clara Valley is an American story of the development of agricultural lands and the transformation of rural regions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aAgriculture and statezCaliforniazSanta Clara Valley (Santa Clara County) 0aAgriculture and statezCaliforniazSanta Clara Valley (Santa Clara County). 0aHigh technology industriesxEnvironmental aspectszCaliforniazSanta Clara Valley (Santa Clara County) 0aHigh technology industriesxEnvironmental aspectszCaliforniazSanta Clara Valley (Santa Clara County). 7aHISTORY / Historical Geography.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520389601?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520389601423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520389601/original  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY